These garlands, he says, are worn in memory of the victory at Thyrea by the leaders of the choruses which dance on the festival of that victory, which coincides with the Gymnopaidiae or Feast of Naked Youths. These choruses are three in number, the youths in front, the old men on the right, and the men on the left3 and they dance naked, singing songs by Thaletas and Alcman and the pacans of the Spartan Dionysodotus.
